NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk about the bidding. First of all 3@C bid.  That is a "reverse" in the sense that Ruth bypassed 2@S. The question is, does it show extra values in 2/1.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In SAYC it definitely does. But in 2/1 there are a couple of options. You could play that it indeed shows extra values. But another way to play is that it shows either a good 4-card suit, or 5-5. The reason opener should be reluctant to bid 3@C is it takes up a lot of room. So most experts play it shows something special. In any case 3@C was the best bid by Ruth particularly since she had both 5 clubs and extra values.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There is some controversy over that 3@D bid as well. Some people play it should show diamonds. Others play it is asking for a diamond stopper because with a diamond stopper Liza would normally bid 3N. I like to play it asks, but not all my expert partners agree with me. In any case, I think on this hand Liza should just bid 3N over 3@C.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's continue with the auction as it went. I know Ruth is worried that they have slam. A spade slam is out of the question once Liza bids 3@D. A club slam is possible. The reason a spade slam is not possible is Liza would bid 3@S over 3@C with 3-card support. So Ruth knows they don't have a spade fit. |
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And although Ruth has more than a min hand (15 HCP) and nice distribution she has some downgradeable features--a poor spade suit in particular and the @DAQ, although worth 6 points, is a bad feature. Honors in short suits are not worth nearly as much as honors in long suits. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, let's turn Ruth's @DQ into the @CQ (so she had @CAKQ) and Ruth's @DA into the @SA (so she had @SAQ). Now her hand has the same 15 points but is much much better (AQxxx x xx AKQxxx) because her long suits are likely to be much easier to set up. In any case, over 3@D I would have bid 3N with Ruth's hand and over 4@S I certainly would not have tried for slam with a known 7-card fit.|
