^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now let me briefly discuss a Marty Bergen concept he calls "OBAR" bids which apply on this hand. Whenever it goes 1x-p-2x (particularly when x is hearts or spades) he feels that if the opponent just after the 2x bid (East on this hand) is short in suit x, they should take action even with very few points. |
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|He calls it "pre-balancing" or OBAR (which stands for Opponents Bid And Raise). So he would say Ruth should bid 2NT on this auction. 2NT, if you play OBAR, does not mean a strong NT. If  you think about it, that makes no sense. Even if Ruth happened to have a strong NT, that would mean her partner is very weak (since the opponents have at least half the points). |
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So 2N, there is not a strong NT. It is sort of "unusual" in that it is a takeout double for the minors. It tends to show 5-4 as opposed to 5-5 however. Ruth could also decide to make a takeout double, playing OBAR. The only flaw is she has only 3 hearts. But they are pretty good ones, so double would be acceptable as well. The main point is that OBAR allows you to compete more effectively.|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to whether OBAR works on this hand. It probably is a neutral result. We make 2@S, and E/W are down in 3 of a red suit. But in general, if it goes 1x-p-2x-p-p-p, you will not do well on the hand. if you do average consider yourself lucky. Most of the time you will be below average.|
